<doc id="42309" wikidata="Q320346" url="?curid=42309" title="Closure (topology)">
<text>In topology, the closure of a subset of points in a topological space consists of all points in together with all limit points of . The closure of may equivalently be defined as the union of and its boundary, and also as the intersection of all closed sets containing . Intuitively, the closure can be thought of as all the points that are either in or &quot;very near&quot; . A point which is in the closure of is a point of closure of . The notion of closure is in many ways dual to the notion of interior.

==Definitions==

=== Point of closure ===
For formula_1 as a subset of a Euclidean space, formula_2 is a point of closure of formula_1 if every open ball centered at formula_2 contains a point of formula_1 (this point can be formula_2 itself).

This definition generalizes to any subset formula_1 of a metric space formula_8 Fully expressed, for formula_9 as a metric space with metric formula_10 formula_2 is a point of closure of formula_1 if for every formula_13 there exists some formula_14 such that the distance formula_15 (formula_16 is allowed). Another way to express this is to say that formula_2 is a point of closure of formula_1 if the distance formula_19 where formula_20 is the infimum. 

This definition generalizes to topological spaces by replacing &quot;open ball&quot; or &quot;ball&quot; with &quot;neighbourhood&quot;. Let formula_1 be a subset of a topological space formula_8 Then formula_2 is a or of formula_1 if every neighbourhood of formula_2 contains a point of formula_1 (again, formula_16 for formula_14 is allowed). Note that this definition does not depend upon whether neighbourhoods are required to be open.

=== Limit point ===
The definition of a point of closure of a set is closely related to the definition of a limit point of a set. The difference between the two definitions is subtle but important – namely, in the definition of a limit point formula_2 of a set formula_1, every neighbourhood of formula_2 must contain a point of formula_1 , i.e., each neighbourhood of formula_2 obviously has formula_2 but it also must have a point of formula_1 that is not equal to formula_2 in order for formula_2 to be a limit point of formula_1. A limit point of formula_1 has more strict condition than a point of closure of formula_1 in the definitions. The set of all limit points of a set formula_1 is called the . A limit point of a set is also called &quot;cluster point&quot; or &quot;accumulation point&quot; of the set. 

Thus, &quot;every limit point is a point of closure, but not every point of closure is a limit point&quot;. A point of closure which is not a limit point is an isolated point. In other words, a point formula_2 is an isolated point of formula_1 if it is an element of formula_1 and there is a neighbourhood of formula_2 which contains no other points of formula_1 than formula_2 itself.

For a given set formula_1 and point formula_49 formula_2 is a point of closure of formula_1 if and only if formula_2 is an element of formula_1 or formula_2 is a limit point of formula_1 (or both).

===Closure of a set===
The of a subset formula_1 of a topological space formula_57 denoted by formula_58 or possibly by formula_59 (if formula_60 is understood), where if both formula_9 and formula_60 are clear from context then it may also be denoted by formula_63 formula_64 or formula_65 (Moreover, formula_66 is sometimes capitalized to formula_67.) can be defined using any of the following equivalent definitions:
# formula_68 is the set of all points of closure of formula_69
# formula_68 is the set formula_1 together with all of its limit points. (Each point of formula_1 is a point of closure of formula_1, and each limit point of formula_1 is also a point of closure of formula_1.)
# formula_68 is the intersection of all closed sets containing formula_69
# formula_68 is the smallest closed set containing formula_69
# formula_68 is the union of formula_1 and its boundary formula_82
# formula_68 is the set of all formula_84 for which there exists a net (valued) in formula_1 that converges to formula_2 in formula_87

The closure of a set has the following properties.

* formula_68 is a closed superset of formula_1.
* The set formula_1 is closed if and only if formula_91.
* If formula_92 then formula_68 is a subset of formula_94
* If formula_95 is a closed set, then formula_95 contains formula_1 if and only if formula_95 contains formula_99

Sometimes the second or third property above is taken as the of the topological closure, which still make sense when applied to other types of closures (see below).

In a first-countable space (such as a metric space), formula_68 is the set of all limits of all convergent sequences of points in formula_69 For a general topological space, this statement remains true if one replaces &quot;sequence&quot; by &quot;net&quot; or &quot;filter&quot; (as described in the article on filters in topology).

Note that these properties are also satisfied if &quot;closure&quot;, &quot;superset&quot;, &quot;intersection&quot;, &quot;contains/containing&quot;, &quot;smallest&quot; and &quot;closed&quot; are replaced by &quot;interior&quot;, &quot;subset&quot;, &quot;union&quot;, &quot;contained in&quot;, &quot;largest&quot;, and &quot;open&quot;. For more on this matter, see closure operator below.

==Examples==
Consider a sphere in a 3 dimensional space. Implicitly there are two regions of interest created by this sphere; the sphere itself and its interior (which is called an open 3-ball). It is useful to distinguish between the interior and the surface of the sphere, so we distinguish between the open 3-ball (the interior of the sphere), and the closed 3-ball – the closure of the open 3-ball that is the open 3-ball plus the surface (the surface as the sphere itself).

In topological space:
* In any space, formula_102. In other words, the closure of the empty set formula_103 is formula_103 itself. 
* In any space formula_105 formula_106

Giving formula_107 and formula_108 the standard (metric) topology:
* If formula_9 is the Euclidean space formula_107 of real numbers, then formula_111. In other words., the closure of the set formula_112 as a subset of formula_9 is formula_114.
* If formula_9 is the Euclidean space formula_107, then the closure of the set formula_117 of rational numbers is the whole space formula_118 We say that formula_117 is dense in formula_118
* If formula_9 is the complex plane formula_122 then formula_123
* If formula_1 is a finite subset of a Euclidean space formula_105 then formula_126 (For a general topological space, this property is equivalent to the T1 axiom.)

On the set of real numbers one can put other topologies rather than the standard one.
* If formula_127 is endowed with the lower limit topology, then formula_128
* If one considers on formula_127 the discrete topology in which every set is closed (open), then formula_130
* If one considers on formula_127 the trivial topology in which the only closed (open) sets are the empty set and formula_107 itself, then formula_133

These examples show that the closure of a set depends upon the topology of the underlying space. The last two examples are special cases of the following.

* In any discrete space, since every set is closed (and also open), every set is equal to its closure.
* In any indiscrete space formula_105 since the only closed sets are the empty set and formula_9 itself, we have that the closure of the empty set is the empty set, and for every non-empty subset formula_95 of formula_105 formula_138 In other words, every non-empty subset of an indiscrete space is dense.

The closure of a set also depends upon in which space we are taking the closure. For example, if formula_9 is the set of rational numbers, with the usual relative topology induced by the Euclidean space formula_140 and if formula_141 then formula_1 is both closed and open in formula_117 because neither formula_1 nor its complement can contain formula_145, which would be the lower bound of formula_1, but cannot be in formula_1 because formula_145 is irrational. So, formula_1 has no well defined closure due to boundary elements not being in formula_117. However, if we instead define formula_9 to be the set of real numbers and define the interval in the same way then the closure of that interval is well defined and would be the set of all greater than formula_145.

==Closure operator==

A on a set formula_9 is a mapping of the power set of formula_105 formula_155, into itself which satisfies the Kuratowski closure axioms. 
Given a topological space formula_156, the topological closure induces a function formula_157 that is defined by sending a subset formula_158 to formula_159 where the notation formula_160 or formula_161 may be used instead. Conversely, if formula_162 is a closure operator on a set formula_105 then a topological space is obtained by defining the closed sets as being exactly those subsets formula_158 that satisfy formula_165 (so complements in formula_9 of these subsets form the open sets of the topology).

The closure operator formula_167 is dual to the interior operator, which is denoted by formula_168 in the sense that

