==Functions and closure==

===Continuity===

A function formula_282 between topological spaces is continuous if and only if the preimage of every closed subset of the codomain is closed in the domain; explicitly, this means: formula_283 is closed in formula_9 whenever formula_203 is a closed subset of formula_286 

In terms of the closure operator, formula_282 is continuous if and only if for every subset formula_288 
formula_289
That is to say, given any element formula_84 that belongs to the closure of a subset formula_288 formula_292 necessarily belongs to the closure of formula_293 in formula_286 If we declare that a point formula_2 is a subset formula_296 if formula_297 then this terminology allows for a plain English description of continuity: formula_298 is continuous if and only if for every subset formula_288 formula_298 maps points that are close to formula_95 to points that are close to formula_302 Thus continuous functions are exactly those functions that preserve (in the forward direction) the &quot;closeness&quot; relationship between points and sets: a function is continuous if and only if whenever a point is close to a set then the image of that point is close to the image of that set. 
Similarly, formula_298 is continuous at a fixed given point formula_84 if and only if whenever formula_2 is close to a subset formula_288 then formula_292 is close to formula_302

===Closed maps===

A function formula_282 is a (strongly) closed map if and only if whenever formula_203 is a closed subset of formula_9 then formula_312 is a closed subset of formula_286 
In terms of the closure operator, formula_282 is a (strongly) closed map if and only if formula_315 for every subset formula_316 
Equivalently, formula_282 is a (strongly) closed map if and only if formula_318 for every closed subset formula_319

==Categorical interpretation==
One may define the closure operator in terms of universal arrows, as follows.

The powerset of a set formula_9 may be realized as a partial order category formula_321 in which the objects are subsets and the morphisms are inclusion maps formula_322 whenever formula_95 is a subset of formula_324 Furthermore, a topology formula_181 on formula_9 is a subcategory of formula_321 with inclusion functor formula_328 The set of closed subsets containing a fixed subset formula_296 can be identified with the comma category formula_330 This category — also a partial order — then has initial object formula_331 Thus there is a universal arrow from formula_95 to formula_333 given by the inclusion formula_334

Similarly, since every closed set containing formula_335 corresponds with an open set contained in formula_95 we can interpret the category formula_337 as the set of open subsets contained in formula_338 with terminal object formula_339 the interior of formula_340

All properties of the closure can be derived from this definition and a few properties of the above categories. Moreover, this definition makes precise the analogy between the topological closure and other types of closures (for example algebraic closure), since all are examples of universal arrows.

